<article>
    <h1>Singapore in phase 3: What to ex&#xAD;pect</h1>
    <h2>Singapore will en&#xAD;ter phase three of its re&#xAD;open&#xAD;ing on Dec 28. Here is what to ex&#xAD;pect:</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201215/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-12-15"><time>2020-12-15</time></a>
        - <span>THE BIG STORY</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>LEISURE AND SO­CIAL AC­TIV­I­TIES</p>
    <p>• Peo­ple can gather in groups of eight, up from five now. House­holds may also re­ceive up to eight vis­i­tors at any one time.</p>
    <p>• At­trac­tions can ap­ply to in­crease their op­er­at­ing ca­pac­ity from 50 per cent to 65 per cent. Mea­sures must con­tinue to be put in place to pre­vent crowd­ing in pop­u­lar ar­eas.</p>
    <p>• Ca­pac­ity limit for malls will be raised from 10 sq m to 8 sq m per per­son.</p>
    <p>PLACES OF WOR­SHIP</p>
    <p>• Ca­pac­ity for con­gre­ga­tional and other wor­ship ser­vices to be raised to up to 250 peo­ple, in zones of up to 50 peo­ple each.</p>
    <p>• Live per­for­mances for ser­vices held by re­li­gious or­gan­i­sa­tions, as well as rites and pray­ers at places of wor­ship, can re­sume in a lim­ited ca­pac­ity. Wind in­stru­ments like flutes are al­lowed.</p>
    <p>WED­DINGS AND FUNER­ALS</p>
    <p>• Up to eight vis­i­tors can at­tend mar­riage solem­ni­sa­tions held in a home. Cur­rently, only</p>
    <p>10 peo­ple – in­clud­ing mem­bers of the host­ing house­hold, and ex­clud­ing the solem­niser and ven­dors – are al­lowed.</p>
    <p>• Live in­stru­men­tal mu­sic will be al­lowed for wed­dings and funer­als, but not wind in­stru­ments like flutes or sax­o­phones.</p>

